  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Double-entry bookkeeping is an accounting method in which every financial transaction is recorded as equal debits and credits in at least two accounts. The method produces a self-balancing system: because every debit has a corresponding credit, the total of all debit balances must equal the total of all credit balances at any point in time. This equality — verified through the trial balance — makes arithmetic errors detectable and provides a structural check against incomplete recording.\n",
